  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Dream of My Son
  author: Seong Jung-eom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your noble ambitions, towering and resolute through all your days,
    Were cruelly thwarted, never given their full flowering.
    I have not yet returned from the world's distant edge,
    While beneath the pine trees you have already turned to dust.

    Night rain falls upon the mountain temple at the border,
    Autumn wind sweeps along the banks of the Han River.
    Those years of bitter hardship and suffering—
    I wish to speak of them, yet find no words remain.
  footnotes:
    - The poem appears to be occasioned by a dream visitation from the poet's deceased son, suggesting a profound meditation on loss, unfulfilled aspirations, and the passage of time.
    - The pine tree (松) is a traditional symbol in East Asian poetry representing longevity and steadfastness, here contrasting poignantly with the son's premature death.
    - The Han River (漢水) and mountain settings evoke the Korean landscape while carrying the weight of separation between the living and the dead.
